## 8. Data Flow Diagrams (DFD)

### Level 1: System Processes

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    User([User])
    UI[Frontend UI]
    NewsProc[News Processing Engine]
    AuthProc[Authentication Module]
    SummProc[Summarization Engine]
    DB[(MongoDB)]
    ExtNews[NewsAPI]
    ExtAI[Gemini API]

    User -->|Views/Clicks| UI
    UI -->|Login/Register| AuthProc
    UI -->|Fetch Category| NewsProc
    UI -->|Request Summary| SummProc
    
    AuthProc <-->|Validate/Store| DB
    NewsProc -->|API Call| ExtNews
    SummProc -->|Prompt| ExtAI
    UI -->|Save Article| DB
```

---

## 9. Sequence Diagrams

### Use Case: AI Summarization Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    actor User
    participant Frontend as Web UI
    participant Backend as Express API
    participant Cache as Redis/Memory
    participant Gemini as Gemini Pro API

    User->>Frontend: Clicks "Summarize"
    Frontend->>Backend: POST /api/news/summarize { article_url }
    
    Backend->>Cache: Check for existing summary (Key: article_url)
    
    alt Cache Hit
        Cache-->>Backend: Returns cached summary
    else Cache Miss
        Backend->>Gemini: POST Prompt ("Summarize this text into 3 bullets: ...")
        Gemini-->>Backend: Returns AI Response
        Backend->>Cache: Store summary with TTL (e.g., 24h)
    end
    
    Backend-->>Frontend: JSON { summary: [...] }
    Frontend-->>User: Renders 3 bullet points
```

---

## 10. Deployment Architecture

For a production-grade deployment on AWS/GCP:

- **Frontend:** Compiled to static files (`npm run build`) and hosted on a CDN (Vercel, AWS CloudFront, or Netlify) for global edge caching.
- **Backend:** Deployed via Docker containers on AWS ECS, Google Cloud Run, or a standard EC2 instance with PM2.
- **Load Balancer:** Distributes traffic across multiple instances of the backend.
- **Database:** Managed MongoDB service (MongoDB Atlas) for automated backups, scaling, and high availability.
- **CI/CD:** GitHub Actions to run tests, build Docker images, and push updates seamlessly to the cloud.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Client([User Browser])
    CDN[Frontend CDN / Vercel]
    LB[API Load Balancer]
    
    subgraph Backend Cluster
        API1[Node.js Instance 1]
        API2[Node.js Instance 2]
    end
    
    DB[(MongoDB Atlas)]
    Cache[(Redis Cache)]
    
    Client -->|Static Assets| CDN
    Client -->|API Data| LB
    LB --> API1
    LB --> API2
    API1 --> DB
    API2 --> DB
    API1 --> Cache
    API2 --> Cache
```

---

## 11. Scalability & Performance

- **Caching:** Crucial for this application. Caching NewsAPI responses prevents rate limits and speeds up the "Live News Feed". Caching Gemini responses prevents redundant LLM processing costs.
- **Horizontal Scaling:** The Node.js backend should be stateless. JWTs manage sessions, allowing the backend to scale horizontally across multiple instances behind a load balancer.
- **Pagination:** Implement cursor-based or offset pagination on the news feed to prevent memory overload on both frontend and backend.
- **Async Processing:** If summarization takes too long, implement WebSockets or Long Polling, though Gemini Pro usually responds fast enough for standard HTTP request-response cycles.

---

## 12. Security Architecture

- **Authentication:** JWT (JSON Web Tokens) stored in secure, `HttpOnly` cookies (recommended) or memory to prevent XSS attacks.
- **Authorization:** Route protection middleware ensures only logged-in users can save articles or request AI summaries.
- **Rate Limiting:** Protect the `/api/summarize` endpoint explicitly. LLM endpoints are targets for abuse. Limit to X requests per IP/User per hour.
- **Input Validation:** Sanitize all incoming requests (especially article URLs and Auth payloads) using a library like Joi or Zod to prevent NoSQL Injection.
- **CORS:** Restrict Cross-Origin Resource Sharing to only the production frontend URL.
- **Environment Secrets:** API Keys (NewsAPI, Gemini) and DB credentials must reside in `.env` files and secret managers in production, never committed to VCS.

---

## 13. Observability

- **Logging:** Implement structured logging (e.g., using `Winston` or `Pino`). Log all API hits, errors, and external API latency.
- **Monitoring:** Track the usage of the Gemini API and NewsAPI carefully to ensure cost control and rate-limit safety.
- **Tracing:** Use a tool like Sentry or Datadog to capture unhandled exceptions in real-time, complete with stack traces and user context.
